"Herold N., Huber M., Müller R.D.","Modeling the miocene climatic optimum. Part I: Land and atmosphere",2011,"Journal of Climate","24","24",,"6353","6373",,,10.1175/2011JCLI4035.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84155175746&partnerID=40&md5=2cd8ca2cbb24c8f2222da37b12284283","EarthByte Group, School of Geosciences, University of Sydney, Sydney, NSW, Australia; Earth and Atmospheric Sciences, Purdue University, West Lafayette, IN, United States; EarthByte Group, School of Geosciences, University of Sydney, Sydney, NSW, Australia","Herold, N., EarthByte Group, School of Geosciences, University of Sydney, Sydney, NSW, Australia; Huber, M., Earth and Atmospheric Sciences, Purdue University, West Lafayette, IN, United States; Müller, R.D., EarthByte Group, School of Geosciences, University of Sydney, Sydney, NSW, Australia","This study presents results from the Community Climate System Model 3 (CCSM3) forced with early to middle Miocene (~20-14 Ma) vegetation, topography, bathymetry, and modern CO 2. A decrease in the meridional temperature gradient of 6.5°C and an increase in global mean temperature of 1.5°C are modeled in comparison with a control simulation forced with modern boundary conditions. Seasonal poleward displacements of the subtropical jet streams and storm tracks compared to the control simulation are associated with changes in Hadley circulation and significant cooling of the polar stratosphere, consistent with previously predicted effects of global warming. Energy budget calculations indicate that reduced albedo and topography were responsible for Miocene warmth in the high-latitude Northern Hemisphere while a combination of increased ocean heat transport and reduced albedo was responsible for relative warmth in the high-latitude Southern Hemisphere, compared to the present. Model-data analysis suggests Miocene climate was significantly warmer and wetter than simulated here, consistent with previous uncoupled Miocene models and supports recent reconstructions of Miocene CO 2 substantially higher than present. © 2011 American Meteorological Society.","Carbon dioxide; Climate change","Community climate system model; Control simulation; Energy budgets; Global-mean temperature; Hadley circulation; Meridional temperature gradient; Middle Miocene; Miocene; Northern Hemispheres; Ocean heat transport; Polar stratosphere; Southern Hemisphere; Storm track; Subtropical jet; Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Computer simulation; Global warming; Solar radiation; Upper atmosphere; Climate models; boundary condition; carbon dioxide; climate modeling; climate variation; Hadley cell; jet stream; Miocene; Northern Hemisphere; paleoclimate; paleotemperature; reconstruction; storm track; stratosphere; temperature gradient",,,,,,"Akgün, F., Kayseri, M.S., Akkiraz, M.S., Palaeoclimatic evolution and vegetational changes during the late Oligocene-Miocene period in western and central Anatolia (Turkey) (2007) Palaeogeogr., Palaeoclimatol., Palaeoecol., 253, pp. 56-90; Barron, E.J., Peterson, W.H., The Cenozoic ocean circulation based on ocean general circulation model results (1991) Palaeogeogr., Palaeoclimatol., Palaeoecol., 83, pp. 1-28; Beerling, D., Berner, R.A., Mackenzie, F.T., Harfoot, M.B., Pyle, J.A., Methane and the CH 4 related greenhouse effect over the past 400 million years (2009) Amer. J. Sci., 309, pp. 97-113; Bice, K.L., Scotese, C.R., Seidov, D., Barron, E.J., Quantifying the role of geographic change in Cenozoic ocean heat transport using uncoupled atmosphere and ocean models (2000) Palaeogeogr., Palaeoclimatol., Palaeoecol., 161, pp. 295-310; Bohme, M., Bruch, A.A., Selmeier, A., The reconstruction of early and middle Miocene climate and vegetation in Southern Germany as determined from the fossil wood flora (2007) Palaeogeogr., Palaeoclimatol., Palaeoecol., 253, pp. 107-130; Boos, W.R., Kuang, Z., Dominant control of the South Asian monsoon by orographic insulation versus plateau heating (2010) Nature